"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148919","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-21","<p>While each security pass application is scrutinised to ensure the applicants credentials, our access control system database does not differentiate between industry employee status or the mode in which they work.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-21T16:40:02.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148919/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148919/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-14","Department for Transport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many (a) aviation, (b) rail and (c) maritime industry employees have security passes for access to the Department for Transport.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148920","Treasury","false","2019-10-22","<p>In 2006, Parliament introduced stringent rules requiring all UK tobacco manufacturers to control their supply chains. These rules required them to take steps to avoid supplying cigarettes and hand rolling tobacco to persons who are likely to smuggle them into the UK or resupply them to other persons who are likely to do the same.</p><p> </p><p>Tobacco manufacturers can face penalties of up to £5m for failing to comply with the rules.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) robustly challenge tobacco manufacturers’ supply chain policies and procedures to ensure their continued compliance with the rules. This has involved ongoing contact and regular meetings between HMRC’s Large Business Team and manufacturers since the legislation was introduced.</p><p> </p><p>One aspect of this ongoing contact is the requirement that manufacturers inspect seizures of over 100,000 cigarettes or 50kg of hand rolling tobacco and provide a summary of how those goods, if confirmed genuine, got in to the hands of smugglers. Large Business review and challenge these summaries to ensure manufacturers have taken appropriate action, in line with their own published supply chain policies.</p><p> </p><p>Due to taxpayer confidentiality it is not possible to provide comment on the progress of HMRC’s discussions with individual businesses about their supply chain controls.</p>","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Mr Simon Clarke","233 ; 266 ; 540 ; 541","2019-10-22T11:08:27.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148920/answer","Biography information for Mr Simon Clarke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1148920/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-14","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what powers he has to sanction tobacco manufacturers for failing to control their supply chain and prevent contraband tobacco entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Charlie Elphicke","Dover","Charlie Elphicke","229"
